subject: How To
content.name: Module 3.2: Action Planning and Commitment to Inclusive Sanitation
content.description:
Welcome to the final module ‘Action planning and commitment to inclusive sanitation’, which delves into an activity that will serve as a platform to consolidate knowledge and learnings gained throughout this training module. 

Its primary objective is to inspire participants to envision and formulate practical actions to create inclusive sanitation systems for urban areas. In this session, the participants will focus on specific interventions for Persons with Disabilities & Elderly, Women & Gender Minorities, Children & Caregivers, and Informal Workers & Safai Karamcharis. These interventions encompass aspects of Policy and Advocacy, Design and Participatory Planning, and Skills & Capacity Building. In this session, participants will brainstorm and generate practical ideas and strategies collaboratively, providing comprehensive insights within their local and regional contexts.
content.creator: Building Accessible Safe Inclusive Indian Cities  BASIIC

subject: How To
content.name: Module 3.1 - Exploring Best Practices on Inclusive Sanitation
content.description: Welcome to the next module ‘Exploring innovative solutions and best practices on inclusive sanitation’. In this session, the focus is on showcasing practical examples of inclusive toilet facilities and highlighting their successful implementation and positive impact. Through the two case studies, participants will delve into the importance of considering user-friendly design before construction and effective operations & maintenance post-construction. Key features such as universal accessibility, gender-sensitive amenities, provisions for caregiving and diverse age groups, pay-and-use facilities, alternative revenue models, and maintaining quality while ensuring affordability will be emphasized. These elements are pivotal in developing sustainable and effective inclusive sanitation interventions. Participants will explore real-world examples and glean valuable lessons for creating inclusive and sustainable toilet facilities.
content.creator: Building Accessible Safe Inclusive Indian Cities  BASIIC

content.name: Module 2.2 -   Participatory Planning for Inclusive Sanitation
content.description:
Welcome to the next session ‘Participatory Planning for Inclusive Sanitation’. This session delves into the importance of user-centered designs and participatory methods in planning inclusive public toilets. The session emphasizes the need for meaningful community participation and highlights the benefits of effective engagement strategies such as Mapping and Diagramming, Interviews, Stimulation, and the Diagram Tool. The session will explore participatory methods through two cases studies. 

Participants will explore various tools for participatory planning, aimed at fostering user-centric design and community ownership. They will gain insights into designing public toilets that meet the diverse needs of users and promote inclusion in urban spaces.
content.creator: Building Accessible Safe Inclusive Indian Cities  BASIIC

subject: How To
content.name: Module 2.1 - Planning and Practicing Inclusive Sanitation Projects - Tools, Mandates, and Policies
content.description:
Welcome to the next module ‘Planning and Practicing Inclusive Sanitation Projects - Tools, Mandates, and Policies’. In this session, we will delve into the diverse needs of various user demographics within the context of public toilet facilities, particularly in India. This module highlights the importance of understanding and addressing the distinct requirements of women, persons with disabilities, children, and the elderly. The module will cover how the tangible manifestation of these needs in public toilet facilities. We emphasize a continuous commitment to updating toilet facilities with relevant amenities to ensure inclusivity and accessibility for all.

The participants will be able to explore the inclusive provisions outlined in various guidelines governing public toilets, including the SBM 1.0 and SBM 2.0 guidelines, CPHEEO Guidelines, and the Harmonized Guidelines and Standards for Universal Accessibility in India, 2021. They will also be exposed to a prototype layout for an accessible public toilet layout.
content.creator: Building Accessible Safe Inclusive Indian Cities  BASIIC

subject: How To
content.name: Module 1.2. – Introduction to Inclusive Sanitation Principles
content.description:
Welcome to "Understanding Inclusive Sanitation," a comprehensive guide that delves into the principles and practices extending beyond basic infrastructure. This module aims to help participants grasp the core concept of inclusive sanitation, emphasizing its crucial role in addressing the diverse needs of all community members, especially marginalized and vulnerable groups.

Throughout this module, participants will gain conceptual clarity on inclusive sanitation, recognizing the interconnection and convergence of sanitation initiatives, and inclusive sanitation principles. The participants will learn about the far-reaching consequences of non-inclusive sanitation will be unveiled along with the global and national commitments on sanitation.
content.creator: Building Accessible Safe Inclusive Indian Cities  BASIIC

subject: Overview
content.name: Module 1.1. Overview of the current sanitation situation in India
content.description:
The foundational module "Overview of Sanitation Challenges in India" aims to provide a comprehensive understanding of the key issues surrounding sanitation in the Indian context. It gives insights into the processes essential for effective sanitation management, setting the stage for a deeper understanding of inclusive sanitation practices. Key terminologies essential for understanding Inclusive Sanitation are introduced, including "Marginalised," "Vulnerable groups," "Inclusive," and "Equitable." It will introduce "Citywide Inclusive Sanitation (CWIS)", fostering a holistic view of equitable, safe, and sustainable sanitation. 

In this module, the participants will be able to analyse challenges encountered in public toilets, and gain insights into the processes essential for effective sanitation management. They will gain essential insights into the complexities of inclusive sanitation practices in India, laying the foundation for subsequent modules.
content.creator: Building Accessible Safe Inclusive Indian Cities  BASIIC

subject: Innovation
content.name: Introduction to Enabling Gender Responsive Urban Mobility and Public Spaces in India
content.description: First module of the e-learning course, based on the toolkit "Enabling Gender Responsive Urban Mobility and Public Spaces in India." This initiative, a collaboration between World Bank and the National Institute of Urban Affairs, aims to empower urban planners and community leaders for adopting and implementing gender-inclusive principles in urban mobility and planning projects.

subject: Overview
content.name: Introduction to Enabling Gender Responsive Urban Mobility and Public Spaces
content.description: This module is intended to bridge the knowledge gaps between policy making and program implementation for gender-responsive urban mobility and public space in India. While central and state governments are committed to the goals of gender equality and women’s empowerment, they often need more practical tools and knowledge of how to translate their intentions into actions and to formulate programs to meet such policy objectives. This module is intended to be a practice guide towards introducing gender equality and women’s empowerment principles in designing urban mobility systems and public spaces so that they mitigate rather than reinforce gender inequalities.
content.creator: Sarah Natasha
